Remove HAVE_SPL (#943)

The HAVE_SPL symbol is defined in PHP to indicate the presence of the
spl extension. Since PHP 5.3 the spl extension is always available and
since PHP-7.4 the HAVE_SPL symbol has also been removed.

Updates for PHP 7.3 (#882)

* Fixed infinite iteration on Threaded objects in PHP 7.3

This bug was caused by changes made in https://github.com/php/php-src/commit/d7f2dc4ec651628e10213625db6aee3559e214a9
There are probably better solutions for this, but this was the simplest and least invasive fix I could come up with.

* Fixed Threaded->chunk() odd behaviour on PHP 7.3

This issue is described in pmmp/pthreads#1. I think move_forward from a non existing index to an existing one is probably undefined behaviour anyway, so this PR prefers using reset, which is also backwards compatible with 7.2.

* fixes for persistent strings

use interned strings for globals
fixed one incorrect use of persistent string
work around possible bug in php-src in zend_hash_str_update_ptr() - keys inserted like this inherit persistence from their parent htable, which is not expected for the global function_table

* fix some socket tests on 7.3

* Make sure that keys are copied when iterating

Previously this would yield persistent strings from the props table. Inserting these strings into standard arrays would then cause issues later on.

* Fixed constant copying on 7.3

* cast zend_object_handlers*, duplicate test for php 7.3+

Fixed unnecessary method signature BC breaks in PHP 7.1+
In PHP 7.1+, these resulted in the signatures becoming `?typehint`, which raises warnings when upgrading old code which overrides these methods. As it turns out, these parameters are not supposed to accept null at all (see the arginfo).
These nullable flags are not necessary; it is sufficient to declare that only X parameters are needed.

This will break code written for pthreads 3.1.7dev which gave null explicitly to these methods; however the fact that these methods accept null is not documented anywhere and I think it is a bug.
This is backwards compatible with code which overrides these methods since parameter type widening allows this.

This has now been properly cleaned up, where any ce copying logic that

Resolve incomplete class warnings when arrays are used as static members

This occurs due to the serializing of static member arrays, where if
an element of that array references a class that has not yet been
prepared, then it will not be able to resolve the class name properly.

The fix is simple: prepare all classes for a thread before attempting
to prepare their static members, thereby circumventing the above problem.

Solution to the problem of arrays ...
Arrays were slow, and difficult to use correct because they behave surprisingly as a result of serialization.
An array is not a thread safe structure, there is no way to share them in many contexts sanely.
Instead, when an array is set as a member of a threaded object, it is coerced to a volatile object, this allows
us to:
	- avoid serialization of arrays (!!!!!!!!!!!)
	- avoid slowdown caused by manipulation of arrays by many threads
	- have arrays that are being manipulated in multiple contexts behave the same as a zend array
	- be delicious
Initial testing has taken place, Threaded ojects are now much more consistent with arrays in general, which is nice.

this commit introduces the concept and implementation of volatile objects whose
members are excempt from immutability rules for normal Threaded objects
they are slow and unpredictable and are treated as such internally
a volatile object should be a special case, the normal case should be to synchronize with
a Threaded object and mutate it's mutatable members rather than use a volatile object that
will perform badly

Volatile: adjective, "liable to change rapidly and unpredictably, especially for the worse."

Improve referencing and storage, implement immutability for Threaded members of Threaded objects
There is a huge cognitive overhead of having to trace the references to all your own objects.
This commit reduces the overhead to nil by placing the simple restriction that a Threaded member of a Threaded
object is immutable for the lifetime of the object.
This commit improves performance of interacting with Threaded members of Threaded objects hugely.

Destroy PTHREADS_ZG(resources) through ZEND_MODULE_POST_ZEND_DEACTIVATE_D callback instead of through PHP_MSHUTDOWN_FUNCTION

contrary to what I thought, PHP_MSHUTDOWN_FUNCTION is not symmetrical to PHP_MINIT_FUNCTION and is only called once when the main thread exits.

PTHREADS_ZG(resources) destroyed too early

It was destroyed before destroying EG(symbol_table): resources marked for keeping would be destroyed if stored in local variables inside ::run() and not destroyed in user-land before the end of the process.

PTHREADS_ZG(resources) is now marked as persistent and destroyed in PHP_MSHUTDOWN_FUNCTION instead of PHP_RSHUTDOWN_FUNCTION. Since PTHREADS_ZG(resources) is necessarily left empty at the end of a request, there is no memory waste.

Merge pull request #404 from 2072/resourcesFix

Multiple fixes to shared resource handling/keeping

Foreign resources could only be extracted from a pthreads_storage if not already added to EG(regular_list).
The reference was just wrong otherwise.

Fix address collision in PTHREADS_ZG(resources)

Each time a resource created in another thread context is used, its address is added to PTHREADS_ZG(resources). Until then it was never removed and since PTHREADS_ZG(resources) is tested on every resource destruction attempt, collisions would occur after some time (when PTHREADS_ZG(resources) contains a few hundred addresses) preventing unrelated resources from being destroyed and causing memory access violations.

This fix removes resources from PTHREADS_ZG(resources) when their dtor is called.

Note that this fix uncovers another bug: PTHREADS_ZG(resources) is destroyed before EG(symbol_table) which prevent resources to be kept in ::run() 'local' variables when a worker is terminated.

Fixed segfault with some compilers in store.c

Fixed segfault with some compilers in store.c

There was no sequence point, so the compiler might first pass the value of key (which is then ((char *)bogus heap memory)) to zend_hash_del_key_or_index and only then fetch the value of key via zend_hash_get_current_key_ex.
Separating it into two different statements inserts a sequence point there so that key is guaranteed to be a valid pointer.
